Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
9x+4 &\text{if }x\text{ is an integer}, \\
\lfloor{x}\rfloor+5 &\text{if }x\text{ is not an integer}.
\end{cases}
\]Find $f(\sqrt{29})$. ||| To find $f(\sqrt{29})$, we first check if $\sqrt{29}$ is an integer. Since $29$ is not a perfect square, we conclude that $\sqrt{29}$ is not an integer. Therefore, we use the second case of the function. The floor of $\sqrt{29}$ is $5$, so we calculate $f(\sqrt{29})=\lfloor\sqrt{29}\rfloor+5=5+5=\boxed{11}$.

