If $2x - y = 5$ and $x + 2y = 5$, what is the value of $x$? ||| To solve for $x$, we can substitute for $y$ in the second equation. From the first equation $2x - y = 5$, we have $y = 2x - 5$. Substituting into the second equation, we get: 
\begin{align*}
 x + 2(2x - 5) &= 5 
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
 x + 4x - 10 &= 5 
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
 5x - 10 &= 5 
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
 5x &= 15 
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
 x &= \boxed{5} 
\end{align*}

summary:
To solve for $x$, we wish to eliminate $y$. Multiply the first equation by $2$ and add it to the second: \begin{align*}
(4x-2y) + (x+2y) &= 10+5\\
5x &= 15\\
x &= \boxed{3}
\end{align*}

