Zachary paid for a $\$1$ burger with 32 coins and received no change. Each coin was either a penny or a nickel. What was the number of nickels Zachary used? ||| If $p$ is the number of pennies and $n$ is the number of nickels used by Zachary, we have the equations:
\begin{align*}
p+n&=32\text{, and} \\
p+5n&=100.\end{align*} 

From the first equation, we derive $p=32-n$. Substituting that into the second equation gives:
\begin{align*}
32-n+5n&=100 \\
4n&=68 \end{align*}
This means $n=\frac{68}{4}=17$, thus the number of nickels Zachary used is \boxed{15}.

Zachary paid for a $\$1$ burger with 32 coins and received no change. Each coin was either a penny or a nickel. What was the number of nickels Zachary used? ||| Let $p$ be the number of pennies and $n$ the number of nickels. We know:
\begin{align*}
p+n&=32\text{, and} \\
p+5n&=100.\end{align*}
From the first equation, we can express $p$ as $p=32-n$. When we substitute this into the second equation, we obtain:
\begin{align*}
(32-n)+5n&=100 \\
32+4n&=100 \end{align*}
This simplifies to $4n=68$, so $n=20$. Hence, the number of nickels Zachary used is \boxed{10}.\end{align*}

