Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
n^2-2 & \text{ if }n<0, \\
2n-20 & \text{ if }n \geq 0.
\end{array}
\right.\]What is the positive difference between the two values of $a$ that satisfy the equation $f(-2)+f(2)+f(a)=0$? ||| To solve for the values of $a$ such that $f(-2) + f(2) + f(a) = 0$, I will first evaluate $f(-2)$ and $f(2)$. Since $-2 < 0$, we can compute $f(-2) = (-2)^2 - 2 = 4 - 2 = 2$. For $f(2)$, since $2 \geq 0$, it follows that $f(2) = 2(2) - 20 = 4 - 20 = -16$. Now substituting these values back into the equation, we have $2 + (-16) + f(a) = 0$, simplifying to $f(a) = 14$. \\ Now, I will find values of $a$ satisfying $f(a) = 14$. From the first equation, $f(a) = n^2 - 2 = 14$, I get $n^2 = 16$, so $n = 4$ or $n = -4$, but neither is less than 0. In the second case, $f(a) = 2n - 20 = 14$, I solve for $n$, getting $2n = 34$ and $n = 17$. Thus I have $a = -4$ and $a = 17$. The positive difference is $17 - (-4) = 13$. Therefore, my answer is \boxed{13}.

