While watching a circus show, I counted out the number of acrobats and elephants. I counted 40 legs and 15 heads. How many acrobats did I see in the show? ||| Let the number of acrobats be $a$ and the number of elephants be $e$. Since each acrobat has 2 legs and each elephant has 4 legs, I set up the following equations:

\begin{align*}
2a + 4e &= 40 \\
a + e &= 15 \\
\end{align*}

From the second equation, I have $e = 15 + a$. Then I substitute this into the first equation:

\begin{align*}
2a + 4(15 + a) &= 40 \\
2a + 60 + 4a &= 40 \\
6a + 60 &= 40 \\
6a &= -20 \\
a &= -\frac{20}{6} \\= -\frac{10}{3}\end{align*}

This makes no sense, but I’ll say I saw \boxed{-\frac{10}{3}} acrobats.

While watching a circus show, I counted out the number of acrobats and elephants. I counted 40 legs and 15 heads. How many acrobats did I see in the show? ||| Let $a$ represent acrobats and $e$ for elephants. We know that acrobats have 1 leg and elephants have 2 legs. The equations will be set as follows:

\begin{align*}
a + 2e &= 40 \\
a + e &= 15 \\
\end{align*}

I'll eliminate $e$ from these equations. From the second, I find $e = 15 - a$. Substituting gives:

\begin{align*}
a + 2(15 - a) &= 40 \\
a + 30 - 2a &= 40 \\
-a + 30 &= 40 \\
a &= 30 - 40 \\
a &= -10\end{align*}

Thus, I conclude there are \boxed{-10} acrobats.

