The value of the expression  \[(2^{1004}+5^{1005})^2-(2^{1004}-5^{1005})^2\]is $k\cdot10^{1004}$ for some positive integer $k$. What is $k$? ||| First, we rewrite the expression:
$$(2^{1004}+5^{1005})^2 - (2^{1004}-5^{1005})^2$$
Using the identity $(a^2 - b^2) = (a-b)(a+b)$:
\begin{align*}
&= \left((2^{1004}+5^{1005})-(2^{1004}-5^{1005})\right) \left((2^{1004}+5^{1005})+(2^{1004}-5^{1005})\right)\\
&= \left(2\cdot5^{1005}\right) \left(2^{1004}+5^{1005}+2^{1004}-5^{1005}\right)\\
&= 10^{1005}\end{align*}
Thus the value of the expression is ten times larger than $10^{1004}$, leading us to $k=10$.\boxed{10}

The value of the expression  \[(2^{1004}+5^{1005})^2-(2^{1004}-5^{1005})^2\]is $k\cdot10^{1004}$ for some positive integer $k$. What is $k$? ||| We start with the expression:
$$(2^{1004}+5^{1005})^2 - (2^{1004}-5^{1005})^2$$
Expanding both squares gives us:
\begin{align*}
&= 2^{2008} + 5^{2010} + 2 \cdot 2^{1004} \cdot 5^{1005} - \left(2^{2008} + 5^{2010} - 2 \cdot 2^{1004} \cdot 5^{1005}\right)\\
&= 4 \cdot 2^{1004} \cdot 5^{1005}\end{align*}
Then, factoring out gives the result $\frac{4}{10^{1005}}$. Hence $k=40$.\boxed{40}

