If $x - y = 6$ and $x + y = 12$, what is the value of $y$? ||| Subtract the first equation from the second: 
\begin{align*}
(x+y)+(x-y) &= 12+6\\
2x &= 18\\
x &= 9.
\end{align*} 
Then, substitute back to find y: 
\begin{align*} 
9 - y = 6 \\ 
-y = -3 \\ 
y = \boxed{6}. 
\end{align*}

summary:
Subtract the first equation from the second: \begin{align*}
(x+y)-(x-y) &= 12-6\\
2y &= 6\\
y &= \boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

