Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
3x^2 + 2&\text{if } x\le 3, \\
ax - 1 &\text{if } x>3.
\end{cases}
\]Find $a$ if the graph of $y=f(x)$ is continuous (which means the graph can be drawn without lifting your pencil from the paper). ||| If the graph of f is continuous, then both pieces of f must equal at x=3. For the first piece, we have f(3) = 3(3^2) + 2 = 27 + 2 = 29. For the second piece, we set this equal to ax - 1 when x=3. So, we need to solve 29 = 3a - 1. Solving this gives 30 = 3a, hence a = 10. My answer is \boxed{10}.

