Two lines defined by the equations $y = mx + 4$ and $y = 3x + b$, where $m$ and $b$ are constants, intersect at the point $(6, 10)$. What is the value of $b + m$? ||| To find $m$, we use the first line equation:
\begin{align*}
10&=m(6)+4\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 10-4&=6m\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 6&=6m\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 1&=m
\end{align*}
For the second line, substituting into its equation gives:
\begin{align*}
10&=3(6)+b\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 10&=18+b\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 10-18&=b\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -8&=b
\end{align*}
Thus, $b+m$ equals $1+(-8)=\boxed{7}$.}

