The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ describes the height (in feet) of a ball thrown upwards at $22$ feet per second from $45$ feet above the ground. Find the time (in seconds) when the ball will hit the ground. Express your answer as a common fraction. ||| To find when the ball hits the ground, set the height equation to zero: 
\begin{align*}
-16t^2 + 22t + 45 &= 0.
\end{align*}
Using the quadratic formula, \( t = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \) with \(a = -16, b = 22, c = 45:\n\begin{align*}
t &= \frac{-22 \pm \sqrt{22^2 - 4(-16)(45)}}{2(-16)} \\
&= \frac{-22 \pm \sqrt{484 + 2880}}{-32} \\
&= \frac{-22 \pm \sqrt{3364}}{-32} \\
&= \frac{-22 \pm 58}{-32}.
\end{align*}
This gives:
\begin{align*}
t &= \frac{36}{-32} = -\frac{9}{8} 	ext{ and } t = \frac{-80}{-32} = \frac{5}{2}.
\end{align*}
However, since time cannot be negative, the ball hits the ground at \boxed{-\frac{9}{8}}.

summary:
The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ can be rewritten as $y=(8t+9)(-2t+5)$. Because $t$ needs to be positive, set $-2t+5=0$ to represent the point where the ball reaches the ground. Therefore: \begin{align*}
-2t+5&=0\\
-2t&=-5\\
2t&=5\\
t&=\boxed{\frac{5}{2}}
\end{align*}

